  "prompt": "What should every first time anime convention goer know?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a comprehensive guide for first-time anime convention attendees, covering everything from preparation to etiquette to making the most of your experience:\n\n**I. Before You Go: Preparation is Key!**\n\n*   **Research the Convention:**\n    *   **Official Website is Your Best Friend:**  Read the convention's website *thoroughly*.  Pay attention to:\n        *   **Schedule:** Panel times, guest appearances, screenings, concerts, contests, etc.\n        *   **Map:**  Get familiar with the layout to avoid getting lost.\n        *   **Rules and Policies:**  Cosplay guidelines, prop regulations, code of conduct (very important!), bag check policies, etc. Don't be *that* person who brings a disallowed weapon.\n        *   **Registration Information:** Where to pick up badges, hours, etc.\n    *   **Social Media/Forums:**  Look for the convention's official social media pages (Facebook, Twitter, etc.) or related forums/Discord servers.  Attendees often share tips, ask questions, and coordinate meetups there.\n*   **Plan Your Schedule (But Be Flexible):**\n    *   **Prioritize:**  Identify the panels, guests, and events you *absolutely* want to see.  Put them on a schedule.\n    *   **Build in Buffer Time:**  Don't pack your schedule too tightly.  Lines, navigation, and spontaneous events can throw off your timing.  Leave time to wander the dealer's room, take breaks, and meet people.\n    *   **Have a Backup Plan:**  Popular events can fill up quickly. Have alternatives in mind in case your first choice is full.\n*   **Budget and Spending:**\n    *   **Set a Budget:**  It's easy to overspend at a convention.  Decide how much you're willing to spend on merchandise, food, and other expenses *before* you go.\n    *   **Cash is King (Sometimes):** While many vendors accept cards, some smaller artists and independent sellers might prefer or only accept cash.  Have a mix of cash and a credit/debit card.\n    *   **Factor in Food and Drink:** Convention food is often overpriced.  Consider bringing your own snacks and drinks (check the convention's rules on outside food/drink).  Factor in the cost of meals, especially if you plan to eat at nearby restaurants.\n*   **Cosplay (If You're Cosplaying):**\n    *   **Plan Well in Advance:**  Don't start your cosplay the day before the convention.  Give yourself plenty of time to create or purchase it.\n    *   **Comfort is Key:**  You'll be wearing your cosplay for hours.  Make sure it's comfortable to walk, sit, and move in.  Test it out before the convention.\n    *   **Prop Rules:**  Familiarize yourself with the convention's prop policy.  This usually covers size, materials, and whether props need to be peace-bonded (marked as non-functional).\n    *   **Pack a Repair Kit:**  Bring a small kit with safety pins, glue, thread, needle, scissors, and other essentials for quick cosplay repairs.\n    *   **Consider a \"Closet Cosplay\":** If you're short on time or budget, consider a \"closet cosplay\" \u2013 using clothes you already own to create a character look.\n*   **Pack the Essentials:**\n    *   **Badge:**  The most important item!  Keep it in a safe and easily accessible place (lanyard recommended).\n    *   **ID:**  For age verification (if needed) and emergencies.\n    *   **Comfortable Shoes:**  You'll be doing a lot of walking.  Trust me on this one.\n    *   **Water Bottle:** Stay hydrated!\n    *   **Snacks:**  To keep your energy up between meals.\n    *   **Hand Sanitizer/Wipes:** Conventions can be crowded.\n    *   **Portable Charger/Power Bank:**  For your phone.\n    *   **Medications:** If you take any prescription or over-the-counter medications, bring them with you.\n    *   **Emergency Contact Information:**  In case of an accident.\n    *   **Small Backpack/Bag:** To carry your essentials.\n    *   **Deodorant:** Please, for everyone's sake.\n*   **Hotel (If Applicable):**\n    *   **Book Early:** Convention hotels tend to fill up quickly and become more expensive closer to the event.\n    *   **Consider Location:** Choose a hotel that's close to the convention center or has convenient transportation options.\n    *   **Share a Room (If Possible):**  Splitting a hotel room with friends can save money.\n*   **Prepare for Sensory Overload:** Conventions are loud, crowded, and visually stimulating. If you're sensitive to these things, consider bringing earplugs or taking breaks in quieter areas.\n\n**II. At the Convention: Navigation and Etiquette**\n\n*   **Badge Pickup:**\n    *   **Go Early:**  Lines for badge pickup can be long, especially on the first day.  Try to pick up your badge as early as possible.\n    *   **Have Your ID Ready:** You'll need to show your ID to pick up your badge.\n*   **Navigating the Crowd:**\n    *   **Be Mindful of Others:**  Avoid blocking hallways or doorways.\n    *   **\"Excuse Me\":** Use \"excuse me\" when trying to get through a crowd.\n    *   **Keep Moving:**  Don't stop abruptly in the middle of a busy area.\n*   **Cosplay Etiquette:**\n    *   **Ask Before Taking Photos:**  Always ask for permission before taking someone's photo.  Be polite and respectful.  A simple \"May I take your picture?\" goes a long way.\n    *   **Respect Personal Space:**  Don't touch cosplayers without their permission.\n    *   **Compliment, Don't Criticize:**  If you admire someone's cosplay, tell them!  Avoid offering unsolicited criticism.\n    *   **Be Patient:**  Cosplayers often get stopped for photos frequently.  Be understanding if they're busy or need to take a break.\n    *   **Cosplay is Not Consent:**  A costume is not an invitation for harassment or unwanted attention.\n*   **Vendor Hall/Artist Alley Etiquette:**\n    *   **Be Respectful of Artists/Vendors:**  Don't haggle excessively or try to get freebies.\n    *   **Don't Touch Merchandise Without Asking:** Some items may be delicate or valuable.\n    *   **Be Mindful of Space:** Don't block aisles or crowd around booths.\n*   **Panel and Event Etiquette:**\n    *   **Arrive Early:**  Popular panels can fill up quickly. Arrive at least 15-30 minutes early to secure a seat.\n    *   **Be Quiet During Panels:**  Avoid talking or making noise during presentations.\n    *   **Turn Off Your Phone:** Or put it on silent.\n    *   **Respect the Speakers:**  Listen attentively and ask thoughtful questions during Q&A sessions.\n*   **General Hygiene:**\n    *   **Shower Regularly:**  This should be a given, but it's worth mentioning.\n    *   **Wear Deodorant:**  Essential for crowded environments.\n    *   **Be Mindful of Body Odor:**  Especially if you're wearing a heavy or layered cosplay.\n*   **Respect the Rules:**\n    *   **Follow the Convention's Rules:**  These rules are in place for everyone's safety and enjoyment.\n    *   **Listen to Staff:**  Convention staff are there to help.  Follow their instructions.\n*   **Stay Safe:**\n    *   **Buddy System:**  Stay with friends, especially at night.\n    *   **Be Aware of Your Surroundings:**  Pay attention to your belongings and avoid walking alone in dark or unfamiliar areas.\n    *   **Report Suspicious Activity:**  If you see something that doesn't seem right, report it to convention staff or security.\n    *   **Don't Accept Drinks from Strangers:** Be cautious about accepting drinks from people you don't know.\n    *   **Consent is Key:** Make sure any interactions with others are consensual.\n\n**III. Making the Most of Your Experience:**\n\n*   **Be Open to Meeting New People:** Conventions are a great place to connect with fellow fans.  Don't be afraid to strike up conversations.\n*   **Don't Be Afraid to Ask Questions:**  If you're lost or confused, don't hesitate to ask a staff member or another attendee for help.\n*   **Take Breaks:**  Conventions can be overwhelming.  Take breaks throughout the day to rest and recharge.  Find a quiet corner, sit down, and relax for a few minutes.\n*   **Try New Things:** Attend a panel you wouldn't normally go to, sample a new food, or try a new activity.\n*   **Collect Memories:** Take photos, collect autographs, and keep your badge as a memento.\n*   **Post-Con Depression is Real:** It's common to feel down after a convention. Plan something fun to do afterward to ease the transition back to everyday life.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\n*   **Plan ahead.**\n*   **Be respectful.**\n*   **Stay safe.**\n*   **Have fun!**\n\nAnime conventions are a unique and exciting experience. By following these tips, you can ensure that your first convention is a positive and memorable one. Good luck, and have a great time!\n",
